@NODE Installation
@TITLE "wave.player · Installation"


    @{b}Installation@{ub}


    Copy wave.player to players/ subdirectory of your AmiNetRadio
    installation. Restart AmiNetRadio if required.

    Make sure wave.player has a higher priority than the 
    mpeg.player, this can avoid possible problems with mpega.library 
    false detecting WAV files as mpeg streams (you can set priority
    by editing/ creating the <player>.pri files).


@ENDNODE

@NODE FAQ
@TITLE "wave.player · FAQ"


    @{b}Frequently Asked Question@{ub}


    Q: I have a file which is not detected at all.

    A: It's probably a broken file which misses necessary and
       important information. Unsupported files are usually
       detected, but not played.


    Q: When I play 8khz (or smaller) samples I have weird breaks
       in the output.

    A: Use a normal AHI Unit and not the music unit, seems to be 
       a bug in AHI or AmiNetRadio.


    Q: I have a very short sample, when I have repeat enabled
       everything seems to lock up.

    A: This is a problem with AmiNetRadio 3.1. Don't use repeat
       on very small files ( < 1 seconds) for the time beeing.


    Q: I have a relatively short file ( < 1 second). It looks 
       like it's played, but I don't hear anything or just a 
       short 'cluck'.

    A: That's because the sample is too short and therefore the
       buffers of AmiNetRadio are not completly filled. You can
       try to reduce the Audio-Buffer in AmiNetRadio Audio-
       Settings to a smaller value. AmiNetRadio is a streaming
       application and therefore this behavior is normal.

@ENDNODE

@NODE bugs
@TITLE "wave.player · Known Bugs"


    @{b}Known Bugs@{ub}


    no bug is currently known. :)



    BUT if wave.player fails to dedect a .wav file and it falls
    back to mpeg.player it can happen that AmiNetRadio likes to crash
    or to do other weird things. It's some problem in the used
    mpega.library which detects too many files as mpeg stream.
    
    So when you want to report a wave.player crash make sure you
    test w/o mpeg.player installed temporaly.

    (And after this: Don't use the not properly detected WAVE file ;)


@ENDNODE

@NODE history
@TITLE "wave.player · History"


    @{b}History@{ub}


    3.1  (19.09.05)   - Release Candidate 1 (first beta release)

    3.2  (20.09.05)   - Release Candidate 2 (second beta release)

                      - fixed 'fmt ' chunk scan in case some optional
                        information were missing, they are created now
                        manually when required

                      - allows to play back files with wrong aligment,
                        should increase compatibility (KennyR)

                      - 16bit/ mono playback fixed

                      - prefs dispatcher closes muimaster now _after_
                        disposing the object

    3.3  (22.09.05)   - Release Candidate 3
    
                      - fileformat/ streaminfo shows now bits per sample,
                        mono/stereo and compression method

                      - internal cleanups and optimizations

                      - fixed playback of very small samples (well
                        somewhat, certain too small samples are still not
                        played back at all, but it shouldn't crash anymore
                        in worst case)

    3.4  (22.09.05)   - Release Candidate 4
     
                      - internal cleanups and optimizations, complete new
                        build process

                      - added versions tag

    3.5  (23.09.05)   - Release Candidate 5
    
                      - uses now the memory pool of the task for allocations

                      - allow to play back 1bit - 7bit and 9bit - 15bit PCM
                        stereo/mono samples (tested with 12bit only, but
                        theoretical should work with other odd bit samples
                        too, if they exists)

                      - added support for Extensible format

                      - cleaned up debug. wave.player will now also print 
                        out useful information to debug log in non-debug 
                        build when validating a RIFF WAVE file fails.

                      - added support for 24bit and 32bit PCM

    3.6  (24.09.05)   Release Candidate 6
    
                      - added support for A-law and µ-law decoded samples

                      - added support for IEEE Float

    3.7  (24.09.05)   - if it detects a RIFF WAVE file, but does not
                        support it, it will now tell this in the ID field 
                        and just stop the playing. this avoids fallback to 
                        other players who could mis-detect the file and 
                        crash.

                      - allow to play back IBM A-law/ µ-law files (0x101,
                        0x102)

   3.8  (25.09.05)   - 'blockalign' and 'average samples per second' values
                        are created now properly aligned to 8. Fixes playback
                        of 12bit, 18bit, etc. samples in case these values
                        were missing in the header.

                      - fixed calculation of internal sample buffer size,
                        also avoids division by zero (even if that didn't do
                        harm on ppc). Now uses constant buffer size for all
                        kinds of samples.

                      - added a - probably useless - additional sanity check
                        to decode function. sure is sure.

                      - reworte seek support partitially. now returns correct
                        values (sdk documentation was a bit misleading) and
                        should be more error prone in general.

                      - removed useless (and not working) 'workarounds' to
                        fix lockups on too small samples. it's fixed in
                        latest aminetradio > v3.1614 (thx. to ultragelb).

                        Just avoid to use 'repeat' on too small samples with
                        older ANR versions.

    3.9  (26.09.05)   - fills now in STREAMURL (makes Stevo happy ;)

    3.10 (27.09.05)   - first public release

                      - drop files with MP3 compression, so mpeg.player can
                        catch and play them (ToDi)

